1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Wow. Late every day this week.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
We signed CC up for this daycare. It's on the other side of town.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:10,000
The traffic is...

4
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Why didn't I think of this before? Did you know that there is a daycare center opening right here in this building?

5
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:17,000
Is there really?

6
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Now that I own the building, I'm looking for new sources of revenue.

7
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:22,000
And a daycare center?

8
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:27,000
Well, I guess it's not an evil idea. It's just a regular idea.

9
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:31,000
But there's no good laugh for a regular idea.

10
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Welcome to the Sesame Avenue Daycare Center for Infants and Toddlers.

11
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Ah!

12
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:41,000
You remember my cousin, Moe's?

13
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Welcome, children.

14
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Were you painting in the dark?

15
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:47,000
Wait, is this your place, Dwight?

16
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:49,000
Oh, no, no. I like to think of it as the kids' place.

17
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Would you like a tour?

18
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:51,000
I don't think we really need...

19
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Oh, let's take the tour, Pam.

20
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Yeah.

21
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Come on.

22
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Here is the language skills and cognitive development area.

23
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:01,000
These are English, uh, letters.

24
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:03,000
I see you found our magical toy box, Jim.

25
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,000
These are actually forks and knives from the break room.

26
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Jim, to you and me maybe, but come on.

27
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:12,000
To a child's imagination, that's Mr. Fork and Lieutenant Knife and Miss Fork.

28
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,000
And a soy sauce packet.

29
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Oh, that's a good one.

30
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Miss Fork.

31
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:19,000
And a soy sauce packet.

32
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:22,000
Oh.

33
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:24,000
That shouldn't have been in there. I'm embarrassed.

34
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Don't beat yourself up.

35
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
We come fully equipped with a restroom, feeding trough, play bucket,

36
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
and room for a plant in success.

37
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Who will be watching the children?

38
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,000
No one. The door locks from the outside. Escape is impossible.

39
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:37,000
Prove it.

40
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:38,000
What?

41
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:40,000
We're gonna head outside. Give it a whirl.

42
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:42,000
I just want to see how it works.

43
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Oh, no, no, no.

44
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:44,000
I'll tell you this.

45
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:45,000
If this works out, I think we're looking real good.

46
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:47,000
I promise you, that door locks.

47
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:30,000
This is the worst. This is the worst.

48
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:33,000
You were the worst. I hate looking at your face. I want to smash it.

49
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Okay, you know what? I made a mistake.

50
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:37,000
I committed corporate punishment.

51
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:41,000
My bad. It's over. It's done.

52
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:48,000
But my punishment is worse than hell.

53
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Michael's been assigned six hours of mandatory counseling

54
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
with a trained professional.

55
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,000
I actually have a degree in social work.

56
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:57,000
I mean, I know a lot of people would just ask a few standard questions

57
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:02,000
and tick off a few boxes, but chances are some good here.

58
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:04,000
I know what you want to ask me.

59
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Do your mom ever see you naked?

60
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:09,000
We can do this with more privacy.

61
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:13,000
So you can molest me? Okay, I don't think so.

62
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:14,000
We're going to leave the blinds open

63
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,000
so everybody can see what a big failure you are.

64
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,000
That's the key.

65
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Boycott the Steamtown Mall!

66
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:27,000
Everyone, you heard me.

67
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Cancel all your businesses with the Steamtown Mall.

68
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:34,000
I don't do boycotts. I am done with boycotts.

69
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,000
The New York Duds, 1968.

70
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
We had had enough.

71
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:43,000
A bunch of us got together.

72
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Black, white, color didn't matter.

73
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,000
We marched on Kellogg's.

74
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:53,000
Two scoops of raisins in my ass.

75
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Those of us still around got together last year and had a laugh.

76
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
We were fifth graders. What do we know?

77
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,000
The mall itself or the stores in the mall?

78
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:07,000
All of it. The mall, the stores, kiosks.

79
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:08,000
America's one big mall.

80
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,000
Did something happen?

81
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Yeah, something happened. Oh, yeah.

82
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,000
Something happened, Jim.

83
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Tell us what it is.

84
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
I mean, it would really help to get some context

85
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:17,000
so we can get on board.

86
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,000
You don't want to know.

87
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:23,000
Would you like to imagine a place that you feel very peaceful?

88
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
For me, it's the walk from the yogurt shop to my car

89
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:30,000
after I dropped my daughter off on Sunday afternoons.

90
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:36,000
I'm glad Michael's getting help.

91
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:39,000
He has a lot of issues and he's stupid.

92
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:44,000
Look, I'm not going to tell you that we have lower prices.

93
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:48,000
Is price something that is important to you?

94
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Okay. Well, let me know if anything changes.

95
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Pam?

96
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
I can't do this.

97
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
I don't have this sales gene or whatever it is.

98
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,000
Tell me everything's going to be okay.

99
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Everything's going to be okay.

100
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
Tell me I'm good at sales.

101
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:16,000
You're good at sales.

102
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:21,000
The unfair thing about working in sales is that your salary is almost all commission.

103
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:24,000
So if you suck at sales, you make almost no money.

104
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,000
I guess that's fair.

105
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:31,000
Dwight?

106
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:32,000
What?

107
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Did you call all my clients at the mall and cancel all my business while using the F word?

108
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:45,000
Yes, I did. And I'm going to do the same with all of your clients.

109
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:46,000
No, you will not.

110
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Oh, yes, I will. That mall is corrupt.

111
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:51,000
Okay, they're appearances.

112
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:55,000
Okay, Dwight, we can't do that. So why don't you just tell us what happened?

113
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
Yeah, what happened, Dwight?

114
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Okay.

115
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:06,000
You guys know me. You know that I'm not one for fancy things, but there was this one thing.

116
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:14,000
I was in a fancy store and it caught the corner of my eye when I took Moe's down to the mall to get his blood pressure at the Rite Aid.

117
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
I thought, you know, maybe I deserved this.

118
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:20,000
You know, I've had a great crop yield this fall.
